topic_title_clean: Inner Compass AND Openness & Learning Mindset
question_clean: How do you balance being open to new ideas while maintaining your core values and beliefs? Can you provide an example of when this balance was particularly challenging?
suggestion_content_clean: Your reflections show a great start in exploring the balance between new ideas and core values! To deepen your reflection, consider sharing a specific example that illustrates this balance. What was a moment when you felt your beliefs were challenged, and how did you navigate that situation?
final_reflection_clean:
A particularly challenging moment that tested my balance between openness and core values occurred during my time at Pro Femina e.V. I had been tasked with improving donor communication processes, a responsibility that required implementing more structured, automated systems to increase efficiency. However, many team members were deeply committed to a personal, relational approach and feared that automation would erode the human connection at the heart of their work.

At first, I felt torn. On one hand, my consulting background at Simon-Kucher & Partners and McKinsey had ingrained in me a strong belief in data-driven efficiency and structured workflows. On the other hand, I personally valued meaningful communication and understood the team’s emotional investment in their work. I experienced frustration – how could I respect their perspective while also pushing for necessary change? I also felt self-doubt: Was I imposing too much of a rigid mindset on an organization that thrived on relational engagement?

To navigate this tension, I took a step back and focused on understanding both perspectives. Instead of enforcing automation outright, I initiated conversations with the team to pinpoint their deepest concerns. Their fear wasn’t technology itself – it was losing the warmth and authenticity of personal outreach. This realization shifted my approach.

I implemented a phased strategy: introducing CRM Dynamics 365 to handle routine follow-ups while keeping key touchpoints personalized. I also organized feedback sessions to ensure the new system complemented, rather than replaced, the team’s strengths. Initially, there was skepticism, but over time, the team saw that efficiency didn’t have to come at the expense of meaningful relationships.

This experience reinforced a crucial lesson: true leadership isn’t about choosing between efficiency and empathy – it’s about integrating both. By embracing discomfort, engaging in dialogue, and remaining flexible, I learned that adapting to new ideas doesn’t mean abandoning core values; it means strengthening them in new ways.

question: Reflect on a time when you had to step out of your comfort zone to learn something new or tackle a challenging task. How did your openness to vulnerability and change impact your learning and growth?
reflection_snapshot: In the last few months, there was a reorganization of the HR department I work for, and therefore I got a new role. At first, I was resistant to this change because it meant starting over in a different area. In my previous role, I had spent the last three years improving the quality of work and processes and perfecting my job. I struggled with the idea of leaving all that behind and starting again in a new role. I also have to admit that I was afraid of failure. In the past, I often preferred success and confirmation over challenges, which is typical of a fixed mindset. While working on my assignment about the growth mindset, I gained a new perspective that completely changed my mindset. I realized that this change is not a step backward, but an opportunity to grow and move forward. It allows me to acquire new skills, prove my abilities once again, and further develop both professionally and personally. I now understand that staying in my old role would not have given me the same opportunities to learn and grow. I have also noticed that this way of thinking had a positive impact on my colleagues at work, who are also struggling with this reorganization. Of course, it will be a big challenge for all of us, but it can also lead to future growth opportunities. Having a growth mindset has helped me to see this change as a great chance to expand my competencies and take on new challenges with confidence.
suggestion_content: Your reflection shows great insight into your experience with change and growth. It’s clear that you’ve made significant progress in shifting your mindset. topic_title: Vorbereitung: Transformationsprozesse erfolgreich gestalten - Fallstudie Change Management
topic_description: Kontinuierlicher Wandel ist auch aus dem Wissenschaftssystem nicht mehr wegzudenken, wodurch die erfolgreiche Durchführung von Veränderungsprozessen zu einem Kernelement des Wissenschaftsmanagement wird, dessen Bedetung weiter zunimmt. Prozesse und Methoden des angewandten Veränderungsmanagements werden im Workshop vertieft und praxisnah erarbeitet.
question: Was glaubst du, wird für dich bei diesem Thema eine Herausforderung sein? Was kannst du im Moment tun, um, in Bezug auf deine Lernziele, das Beste herauszuholen?
suggestion_content: Es ist großartig, dass du dir Gedanken über deine Herausforderungen machst! Um deine Reflexion zu vertiefen, könntest du darüber nachdenken, wie spezifische Situationen deine Lernziele beeinflussen. Was genau könnte dich daran hindern, erfolgreich zu sein? Und wie kannst du konkret an diesen Herausforderungen arbeiten?
final_reflection:
Ich finde es herausfordernd, mit Widerständen und Unsicherheiten in Veränderungsprozessen umzugehen. Außerdem ist eine effektive Kommunikation zu entwickeln, die alle Beteiligten einbindet, für mich anspruchsvoll.

Ich würde gerne praxisnahe Fallstudien analysieren, um ggf. Lösungsstrategien abzuleiten.
Ich würde aktiv Rückmeldungen/Gespräche mit Kollegen und Seminarteilnehmern einholen und aktiuelle Situationen beobachten und reflektieren.

But my values will power me through all hardship and difficulties. Reaching this carreer will make me feel valuable and like I can make a positive and sustainable contribution to a greater environment. I will feel at peace and content with myself.

topic_description:
Positive goals help you focus, stay motivated, and grow—both in your studies and as a person. In this short exercise, you'll set clear, achievable goals that matter to you, so you can take purposeful steps toward success and get the most out of your university journey.

Rflect team: you can use this exercise to set 1-3 learning goals for yourself in the next 6 months to make it relevant to you.
question:
Step 1: Start With Your "Why". Imagine you’ve had your best semester ever. What made it feel so successful?

Multiple-choice suggestions (choose 1–2):

  • “I felt confident and prepared for exams.”

  • “I stayed organized and on top of my workload.”

  • “I enjoyed learning and made progress I was proud of.”

  • “I felt calm, balanced, and in control.”

  • OR:

    “Describe your best semester in your own words.”

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week, this time with the theme of “Flexibility & Adaptability”, the ability to adjust your thoughts, behaviors, and actions in response to changing circumstances, new information, or unexpected challenges, while maintaining a positive and productive approach.

We will reflect on the previous week, learn about the theme and plan the week ahead.

Why are there themed reflections?

Your innovative study program is aware of the importance of Inner Development in your Education and has decided to offer you Rflect to help you practice those Inner Competencies.

Inner Competences (some call it soft skills, personal development, etc.) are based on your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These competencies shape how we manage ourselves, relate to others, and respond to challenges. They are key to personal development, emotional well-being, and success in both personal and professional spheres. You can find out why there are important here.

Rflect helps you practice inner competencies outlined in the Inner Development Goals (IDG) and beyond.

Every week you will have one topic where you reflect on your personal learning journey and also on 1 of the 23 competencies outlined in the IDG Framework.

For the first semester(s) we will introduce those competencies broadly to you (with a few reflective questions). Later on, we will dive deeper into them and practice them with exercises and actions.
question: The theme of this week is 'Flexibility & Adaptability'. How is this topic relevant for yourself?
reflection_snapshot: I can't answer this as a general question, as it depends enormously on the circumstances that require flexibility. I'm quite flexible and adaptable as long as the result is ok. When the circumstances requiring the mentioned traits lead to a longer phase where important basic needs such as social connection, mental stimulation, and variety are not met, and i can't find any form of compensation or self-efficacy to meet these needs, then i have severe difficulty. So i am flexible unless my non negotiable needs are still met.
suggestion_content: It's great to see you engaging with the theme of flexibility and adaptability! To deepen your reflection, consider how specific situations have challenged your adaptability. What strategies have you used to maintain your basic needs during these times? This could help you explore your experiences further.
final_reflection: I can't answer this as a general question, as it depends enormously on the circumstances that require flexibility. I'm quite flexible and adaptable as long as the result is ok. When the circumstances requiring the mentioned traits lead to a longer phase where important basic needs such as social connection, mental stimulation, and variety are not met, and i can't find any form of compensation or self-efficacy to meet these needs, then i have severe difficulty. So i am flexible unless my non-negotiable needs are still met. And sometimes i am adaptable even when that is not the case but i simply have no other option. So flexibility and adaptability is also  a question of options, i think for everyone.

topic_description: Please answer the following questions AFTER you have had your individual coaching session.
question: In about 300 words, please describe first the 2-3 key insights of your coaching session (eg. What did you realize that you were not aware of before? What beliefs were questioned? Where did you gain greater clarity?). Then describe the 2-3 key actions (eg. What will you do differently in the next semester? How will you show up differently? How will you organize yourself?). Also write down any other thoughts that you believe should be captured here because they are relevant to you.
reflection_snapshot: I didn't really know what to expect of the coaching session, but I immediately felt comfortable to talk about what was bothering me with my coach.
suggestion_content: It's great to see you engaging with your coaching session! Your initial comfort in sharing is a solid foundation. To deepen your reflection, consider exploring what specific insights emerged during your conversation. What beliefs about yourself or your coaching approach were challenged? How might these insights influence your actions next semester?
final_reflection:
I didn’t really know what to expect from the coaching session, but I immediately felt comfortable opening up to my coach about what was bothering me. The session was incredibly helpful in gaining clarity about my current situation and offered me a valuable new perspective on the issues I was facing. At the beginning, my coach guided me through a detailed analysis of the situation, helping me understand why I was feeling the way I did. This structured approach with specific questions, allowed me to see that I can only influence certain things to a limited extent. It also reminded me not to waste energy worrying about things beyond my control. While this is not always easy to accept, I found that every challenge offers an opportunity to learn and grow.  

Looking ahead to the next semester, I want to consciously avoid starting with a negative mindset or always expecting the worst-case scenario. Instead, I will focus on doing my best and trust that everything else will fall into place. If my expectations aren’t met, I’ll remind myself that life goes on. I also want to let go of the habit of holding others to the same expectations I have for myself, as everyone approaches situations differently. Instead of being frustrated when communication isn’t working, I’ll aim to inspire others and seek solutions collaboratively. I’ll also try to work with people who share a similar mindset and approach to problem-solving. 

One of the most valuable insights I gained is the importance of evaluating how significant an issue truly is. By taking a moment to assess whether a problem will still matter to me in two months, I can better prioritize my energy and focus. Often, I’ve realized that some issues that feel overwhelming in the moment aren’t worth worrying about on long-term. With this perspective, I hope to let go of minor frustrations more quickly and channel my energy into what truly matters.

reflection_snapshot:

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week, this time with the theme of “Flexibility & Adaptability”, the ability to adjust your thoughts, behaviors, and actions in response to changing circumstances, new information, or unexpected challenges, while maintaining a positive and productive approach.

We will reflect on the previous week, learn about the theme and plan the week ahead.

Why are there themed reflections?

Your innovative study program is aware of the importance of Inner Development in your Education and has decided to offer you Rflect to help you practice those Inner Competencies.

Inner Competences (some call it soft skills, personal development, etc.) are based on your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These competencies shape how we manage ourselves, relate to others, and respond to challenges. They are key to personal development, emotional well-being, and success in both personal and professional spheres. You can find out why there are important here.

Rflect helps you practice inner competencies outlined in the Inner Development Goals (IDG) and beyond.

Every week you will have one topic where you reflect on your personal learning journey and also on 1 of the 23 competencies outlined in the IDG Framework.

For the first semester(s) we will introduce those competencies broadly to you (with a few reflective questions). Later on, we will dive deeper into them and practice them with exercises and actions.

topic_title: Block 2 Week #6: Start the week: Flexibility and adaptability
topic_description:
Welcome to a new week in Rflect, this time with the focus on “Flexibility and adaptability”.

As usual you start the week with questions on your motivation and needed support.

Flexibility means being able to change your plans, attitudes, or actions when things change or unexpected problems come up.

Adaptability is about being able to quickly learn and adjust to new situations, places, or tasks.

Both skills are crucial for navigating an increasingly fast-paced, unpredictable world, both personally and professionally.

Flexibility and adaptability are vital for growth, problem-solving, and resilience in the face of change or challenges.

Developing these skills allows you to thrive in uncertainty, manage stress more effectively, and seize opportunities even when things don’t go as planned.

question: Can you identify any instances in your educational journey, or life in general, where you had to compromise your values or sense of responsibility? How did you navigate such situations, and what did you learn from them?
reflection_snapshot:
As everybody I have encountered situations where my values have been challenged. Sometimes by, external pressures and sometimes by internal conflicts. 

Examples
As I honour perfection it’s sometimes hard to make my boss’ dreams come true. For example, I have to prepare a keynote for c-level managers about AI and generative AI and also combine it with a workshop part to find some use-cases. In general, I like those kinds of events, and I think of suitable stories to tell to make it a journey for all participants. However, for this one I had just five working days (filled with appointments and other stuff) left. It’s not easy to make the perfect keynote with accurate information and a exciting story. 

Another situation involved my value of sustainability during a project. I made choices that I felt were environmentally wasteful, such as unnecessary over pollution and overuse of resources while still claiming it a green project. While I voiced my concerns, they were not fully addressed due to a bigger interest for profit and easy solutions. I had to proceed with the project despite feeling that it conflicted with my value of concern for the environment.

In both cases, I navigated these situations by focusing on open communication and little steps. I initiated a discussion with my boss and his boss in the first case, explaining my perspective while also listening to theirs. We agreed on a division of tasks that allowed me to focus on critical details while I delegated to others less detail-oriented aspects. This taught me the importance of compromise and delegation without losing sight of my values.

Regarding the sustainability-related project, I chose to frame my concerns constructively, suggesting actionable alternatives for now and for future projects. While I could not change the immediate situation, I felt that proposing solutions upheld my value of sustainability in the long term.

In both cases it was important to me to be flexible in my thinking and still don’t abandoning my values. 
Communication and open  dialogue is the main tool to use, so I can bridge the gap between conflicting priorities, helping to align individual and group objectives.
Very important to me is the focus on the “Bigger Picture”. In some cases, the immediate outcome may not fully align with my values, but small, incremental efforts can lead to broader, long-term change.
suggestion_content: You've done a great job articulating your experiences and the challenges you've faced with your values. It's clear you've put thought into how you navigated these situations. To deepen your reflection, consider how these experiences have shaped your understanding of your values over time. What specific lessons did you take away that might influence your future decisions?

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week, this time with the theme of “Critical Thinking”, skills in critically reviewing the validity of views, evidence and plans. This competence is part of the IDG Thinking-Dimension.

We will reflect on the previous week, learn about the theme and plan the week ahead.

Why are there themed reflections?

Your innovative study program is aware of the importance of Inner Development in your Education and has decided to offer you Rflect to help you practice those Inner Competencies.

Inner Competences (some call it soft skills, personal development, etc.) are based on your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These competencies shape how we manage ourselves, relate to others, and respond to challenges. They are key to personal development, emotional well-being, and success in both personal and professional spheres. You can find out why there are important here.

Rflect helps you practice inner competencies outlined in the Inner Development Goals (IDG) and beyond.

Every week you will have one topic where you reflect on your personal learning journey and also on 1 of the 23 competencies outlined in the IDG Framework.

For the first semester(s) we will introduce those competencies broadly to you (with a few reflective questions). Later on, we will dive deeper into them and practice them with exercises and actions.
question: Think of a situation recently where you were discussing a topic (without your program or outside) in a heated way. Do you feel the other person was open and applied critical thinking to really understand your position? Do you think you were open and applied critical thinking to really understand their position? What can you take from this reflection? How can you practice what you preach and motivate others to do the same?
reflection_snapshot: Dans les deux nous n'avions pas d'esprit critique assez ouvert. Nous n'avons pas essayé de se mettre à la place l'une de l'autre pour mieux comprendre le point de vu de l'autre. Et c'était aussi une situation qui était émotionnellement pas facile pour les deux. Je pense que ce qui nous aurait aidé, aurait été de parler calmement et de laisser nos émotions de côté. De questionner sa position pour mieux la comprendre ou lui montrer que son point de vue n'est pas forcément cohérant. Et vis-et-versa bien sûr.
suggestion_content: C'est super que tu aies pris le temps de réfléchir à cette situation ! Pour approfondir ta réflexion, comment pourrais-tu mieux gérer tes émotions lors de discussions difficiles ? Que penses-tu qu'il serait utile de faire pour encourager l'ouverture d'esprit chez l'autre personne ?
final_reflection: Dans les deux nous n'avions pas d'esprit critique assez ouvert. Nous n'avons pas essayé de se mettre à la place l'une de l'autre pour mieux comprendre le point de vu de l'autre. Et c'était aussi une situation qui était émotionnellement pas facile pour les deux. Je pense que ce qui nous aurait aidé, aurait été de parler calmement et de laisser nos émotions de côté. De questionner sa position pour mieux la comprendre ou lui montrer que son point de vue n'est pas forcément cohérant. Et vis-et-versa bien sûr.

question: The theme of this week is 'Critical Thinking'. How is this topic relevant for yourself?
reflection_snapshot: Je pense qu'il est très important dans la vie, mais en particulier dans le monde scientifique. C'est bien d'avoir un esprit critique dans notre quotidien. Avant de prendre des décisions, j'aime bien réfléchir à la situation et à me poser la question pourquoi. Par exemple, récemment, au travail, on a décidé de me changer rapidement mon contrat de travail. Au lieu de signer directement, j'ai posé certaines questions pour mieux comprendre.
suggestion_content: C'est super que tu reconnaisses l'importance de la pensée critique dans ta vie quotidienne et au travail ! Pour approfondir ta réflexion, pourquoi penses-tu que poser des questions est essentiel avant de prendre une décision ? Comment cela a-t-il influencé ta perception de la situation avec ton contrat ?
final_reflection: Je pense qu'il est très important dans la vie, mais en particulier dans le monde scientifique. C'est bien d'avoir un esprit critique dans notre quotidien. Avant de prendre des décisions, j'aime bien réfléchir à la situation et à me poser la question pourquoi. Par exemple, récemment, au travail, on a décidé de me changer rapidement mon contrat de travail. Au lieu de signer directement, j'ai posé certaines questions pour mieux comprendre. Cela m'a permis de savoir pourquoi il faisait ce changement et quel impact cela avait sur mon travail et mon salaire. Je peux ainsi prendre une décision éclairée.

Avant de prendre des décisions, j'aime bien réfléchir à la situation et à me poser la question pourquoi. Par exemple, récemment, au travail, on a décidé de me changer rapidement mon contrat de travail. Au lieu de signer directement, j'ai posé certaines questions pour mieux comprendre.
suggestion_content_clean: C'est super que tu reconnaisses l'importance de la pensée critique dans ta vie quotidienne et au travail ! Pour approfondir ta réflexion, pourquoi penses-tu que poser des questions est essentiel avant de prendre une décision ? Comment cela a-t-il influencé ta perception de la situation avec ton contrat ?
final_reflection_clean: Je pense qu'il est très important dans la vie, mais en particulier dans le monde scientifique. C'est bien d'avoir un esprit critique dans notre quotidien. Avant de prendre des décisions, j'aime bien réfléchir à la situation et à me poser la question pourquoi. Par exemple, récemment, au travail, on a décidé de me changer rapidement mon contrat de travail. Au lieu de signer directement, j'ai posé certaines questions pour mieux comprendre. Cela m'a permis de savoir pourquoi il faisait ce changement et quel impact cela avait sur mon travail et mon salaire. Je peux ainsi prendre une décision éclairée.

question: Can you identify any instances in your educational journey, or life in general, where you had to compromise your values or sense of responsibility? How did you navigate such situations, and what did you learn from them?
reflection_snapshot:
Navigating professional challenges often tests our values and resilience. One memorable instance in my career occurred when I worked under a narcissistic boss. The work itself was meaningful, and I was genuinely passionate about my role. However, the environment demanded that I prioritize professionalism over values like fairness and transparency. To maintain harmony, I refrained from criticizing him, took blame that wasn’t mine, and avoided confrontation—choices that didn’t sit comfortably with me.

The challenge was twofold: preserving my integrity while navigating a toxic dynamic. Despite the difficulty, I recognized that my immediate goal was to ensure the quality of my work and uphold my professional demeanor. This approach allowed me to stay focused on tasks that mattered to me, but it also made me reflect deeply on the cost of compromising core values. The experience underscored the importance of psychological safety in a workplace and how much it impacts one’s ability to thrive.

Ultimately, my contract ended and wasn’t renewed, which, in hindsight, became a turning point. While the outcome felt disheartening initially, it was liberating to step away from a toxic environment. I gained valuable insights about identifying narcissistic traits early and learned strategies to manage them without losing myself—skills that have since shaped how I approach professional relationships.

This experience has profoundly influenced my approach to workplace dynamics. Since then, I’ve become more deliberate in aligning my values with my professional choices. For instance, during job interviews, I prioritize asking questions about leadership styles and team culture to gauge their compatibility with my principles. In my roles, I actively promote transparency and fairness, such as encouraging open dialogue during team meetings and providing constructive feedback in a respectful manner. These practices ensure that my workplace is not only productive but also aligned with the values I hold dear.

This challenge strengthened my resolve to prioritize meaningful work alongside respectful, value-driven relationships. It also reinforced the belief that thriving professionally requires an environment where both personal growth and collective success can coexist harmoniously.
suggestion_content: You've done a great job reflecting on a challenging experience and how it shaped your professional values. To deepen your reflection, consider exploring how this experience has influenced your interactions with colleagues. What specific strategies do you now employ to foster a positive work environment?
final_reflection:
Navigating professional challenges often tests our values and resilience. One memorable instance in my career occurred when I worked under a narcissistic boss. The work itself was meaningful, but the environment demanded that I prioritize professionalism over values like honesty, fairness and transparency. To maintain harmony, I refrained from criticism, took unwarranted blame, and avoided confrontation – choices that conflicted with my principles.

The challenge lay in preserving my integrity while managing a toxic dynamic. My focus was to maintain the quality of my work and professionalism, but the experience forced me to reflect deeply on the cost of compromising core values. It underscored how essential psychological safety is for thriving in the workplace and how significantly it impacts both individual and team performance.

When my contract ended, it became a turning point. Stepping away from the toxic environment was liberating and gave me clarity. I learned to recognize narcissistic traits early and developed strategies to manage such dynamics while protecting my self-respect. These insights now shape my professional decisions, particularly in selecting roles and environments that align with my values of fairness, transparency, and respect.

This experience also reshaped how I interact with colleagues and foster a positive workplace culture. I prioritize mutual respect through active listening and encouraging open communication, ensuring everyone feels heard. Leading by example, I promote fairness and transparency in decision-making and create a culture where constructive feedback drives growth. During hiring processes, I now ask targeted questions about leadership styles and team culture to ensure alignment with my principles.

These strategies have strengthened my resolve to create environments where values-driven interactions are integral. While compromise is sometimes necessary, it should never come at the expense of dignity or well-being. This challenge ultimately taught me the importance of fostering workplaces where respect, teamwork, and trust are foundational to success and satisfaction.

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week, this time with the theme of “Conflict Management”, the ability to navigate and resolve disputes constructively, ensuring positive outcomes while maintaining relationships and fostering mutual understanding.

We will reflect on the previous week, learn about the theme and plan the week ahead.

Why are there themed reflections?

Your innovative study program is aware of the importance of Inner Development in your Education and has decided to offer you Rflect to help you practice those Inner Competencies.

Inner Competences (some call it soft skills, personal development, etc.) are based on your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These competencies shape how we manage ourselves, relate to others, and respond to challenges. They are key to personal development, emotional well-being, and success in both personal and professional spheres. You can find out why there are important here.

Rflect helps you practice inner competencies outlined in the Inner Development Goals (IDG) and beyond.

Every week you will have one topic where you reflect on your personal learning journey and also on 1 of the 23 competencies outlined in the IDG Framework.

For the first semester(s) we will introduce those competencies broadly to you (with a few reflective questions). Later on, we will dive deeper into them and practice them with exercises and actions.
question: If you were to share one thing from this week with a friend or colleague that you found interesting, surprising, or valuable, what would it be and why?
reflection_snapshot: That we give trees in Swiss cities on average around 8 cubic meter space for their roots. A tree that is standing for about 20 years requires 24 cubic meters. The average life time of a city tree is 30 years. I think it represents this conflict we have with nature. We know we need trees for our health but we struggle to find room for them. It is not very economical in regards to tree and labor cost, Co2 take up and storage to replace a city tree every 20-30years.
suggestion_content: Great job highlighting the importance of trees in urban environments! To deepen your reflection, consider exploring how the conflict between urban development and nature affects community well-being. What solutions could cities implement to create more space for trees while balancing economic needs?
final_reflection: That we give trees in Swiss cities on average around 8 cubic meter space for their roots. A tree that is standing for about 20 years requires 24 cubic meters. The average life time of a city tree is 30 years. I think it represents this conflict we have with nature. We know we need trees for our health but we struggle to find room for them. The way we calculate at the moment, we value apartment and commerce buildings higher for the economy of a town than a tree  who`s roots should not be damaged . So the tree pays the price but ultimately it is us and our health. It is also not very economical in regards to tree purchasing price, labor cost, Co2 take up and storage to replace a city tree every 20-30years. If you compare his functions with a commercial CO2 storage facility we`d be valuing them different. Every tree should have a real time billboard funktion to show how much Co2 he stores, takes up and how many other health benefits he has for us per day and that translated into a monetary value. It would change peoples perception of trees.

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week, this time with the theme of “Empathy & Compassion”, the ability to relate to others, oneself and nature with kindness, empathy and compassion and address related suffering. This competence is part of the IDG Relating-Dimension.

We will reflect on the previous week, learn about the theme and plan the week ahead.

Why are there themed reflections?

Your innovative study program is aware of the importance of Inner Development in your Education and has decided to offer you Rflect to help you practice those Inner Competencies.

Inner Competences (some call it soft skills, personal development, etc.) are based on your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These competencies shape how we manage ourselves, relate to others, and respond to challenges. They are key to personal development, emotional well-being, and success in both personal and professional spheres. You can find out why there are important here.

Rflect helps you practice inner competencies outlined in the Inner Development Goals (IDG) and beyond.

Every week you will have one topic where you reflect on your personal learning journey and also on 1 of the 23 competencies outlined in the IDG Framework.

For the first semester(s) we will introduce those competencies broadly to you (with a few reflective questions). Later on, we will dive deeper into them and practice them with exercises and actions.
question: The theme of this week is 'Empathy & Compassion'. How is this topic relevant for yourself?
reflection_snapshot: It is extremely relevant for me. I used to be told that I seem very empathic in the past, which I think is true. I think it is true because I often feel some kind of sadness over the world, I like to call it "Weltschmerz" when I'm hearing about things that happen on this planet which I think are not good. This is the empathy I feel over the world, however I can as well empathize with my peers.
suggestion_content: It’s great to see you reflecting on empathy and compassion! Your feelings of "Weltschmerz" show a deep awareness of the world around you. How do these feelings influence your interactions with others? Can you think of a specific instance where your empathy made a difference in someone else's life?
final_reflection:
It is extremely relevant for me. I used to be told that I seem very empathic in the past, which I think is true. I think it is true because I often feel some kind of sadness over the world, I like to call it "Weltschmerz" when I'm hearing about things that happen on this planet which I think are not good. This is the empathy I feel over the world. However I can as well empathize with my peers. This allows me to bond with other people more deeply. It requires that I myself am happy to a certain extent and that I am not too busy with my own issues. I sadly have been quite preoccupied with my own life and subjects in the past months which leads currently to my relationships suffering a bit because I'm less accessible, I think. I need to reach out to my family and friends more often, even short calls are worth a lot.

In reference to the societal / political aspect I believe that there is not enough empathy behind a lot of decisions we make. To often we decide selfish and even more often we do not bother to try understanding our opponents which most definitely contributes to the opponents distancing themselves even further from us. We must talk with each other and try to understand without thinking constantly that the opponent is wrong anyway. Politically speaking, we (as a class quite on the left side) need to speak on a deeper level and more seriously with our opponents (our about them at the moment). With a better understanding of our opponents we might get over the surface-level discussions and find compromises on a deeper level.

question: Looking back at this week, is there a moment, insight, or experience that stands out to you? How did it shape your perspective or understanding?
reflection_snapshot: I got flue symptoms on Thursday and on Sunday our working group had an online meeting to work on our presentation. My colleague asked me if she could take some work off me as I had planned to prepare 3 topics. So she took one more topic off my to do list. I was positively surprised and really grateful because I struggled with energy and my flue at this point. Maybe it was a not such a big thing for her  but for me it felt like a huge relieve. I saw that she thought about my situation and decided to offer me some help, even without me asking and even if that meant more work for her. At that moment I was so happy that I had less to worry about. When we were done with the presentation I realized that it was a quite a bit more work she took on, only to help me out. I feel very grateful for such a colleague and will give her that feedback in the next week. It will also be a reminder to look out for opportunities where I can extend a helping hand to someone. Even if I am  not explicitly asked to help, I can offer it.
suggestion_content: Your reflection shows great insight into the importance of teamwork and support, especially during challenging times. To deepen your reflection, consider how this experience might influence your future interactions with colleagues. What specific actions can you take to foster a supportive environment in your group?
final_reflection: I got flue symptoms on Thursday and on Sunday our working group had an online meeting to work on our presentation. My colleague asked me if she could take some work off me as I had planned to prepare 3 topics. So, she took one more topic off my to do list. I was positively surprised and really grateful because I struggled with energy and my flue at this point. Maybe it was a not such a big thing for her but for me it felt like a huge relieve. I saw that she thought about my situation and decided to offer me some help, even without me asking and even if that meant more work for her. At that moment I was so happy that I had less to worry about. When we were done with the presentation I realized how much more work she took on, only to help me out. I feel very grateful for such a colleague and will give her that feedback this week. It will also be a reminder to look out for opportunities where I can extend a helping hand to others. Even if I am not explicitly asked to help, I can offer it. This week I will at least ask on person if i can do something for them. It gives a feeling to be seen and supported especially in difficult times, when a group carries their members.

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week in Rflect, this time with the focus on “Importance and urgency of tasks”.

As usual you start the week with questions on your motivation and needed support.

In this week we will work on determining the importance and urgency of tasks. By using the Eisenhower matrix you will learn to prioritize better and get more insight into how to organize your time effectively. You will discover which tasks are really important and which ones you can postpone or delegate. This skill will help you stay organized, reduce stress and better manage your study and workload. Let's get started!
question: What was the most challenging part of categorizing your tasks? For example did you struggle with determining what’s truly important vs. urgent?
suggestion_content: Your response is a great start, but it feels a bit brief for a reflective exercise. Try to expand on your thoughts by exploring specific examples of tasks you categorized and how you determined their importance versus urgency. This will deepen your reflection and enhance your writing.

By using the Eisenhower matrix you will learn to prioritize better and get more insight into how to organize your time effectively. You will discover which tasks are really important and which ones you can postpone or delegate. This skill will help you stay organized, reduce stress and better manage your study and workload. Let's get started!
question_clean: What was the most challenging part of categorizing your tasks? For example did you struggle with determining what’s truly important vs. urgent?
suggestion_content_clean: Your response is a great start, but it feels a bit brief for a reflective exercise. Try to expand on your thoughts by exploring specific examples of tasks you categorized and how you determined their importance versus urgency. This will deepen your reflection and enhance your writing.
final_reflection_clean: ik wist al wel dat sommige taken niet urgent zijn maar blijf ze wel doen. maar nu realiseer je je wel dat je eigenlijk eerst aan de urgente taken moet beginnen

topic_title: Module Prep - Building and managing your research group
question: Imagine you are in the process of building your team. How would you design the ideal recruiting process to build a strong team? How do you envision the ideal hiring process to find the right person?
reflection_snapshot:
During the finding process:
- Be as explicit as possible in the advertisement
- Showcase our own values and how we work in the hiring process/advert
- Distribute the advert in my own and others network
- Possibly find sb within the network

During interview process:
- Avoid standard procedures
- Talk about values, expectations, examples on how they work: e.g. how did they deal with problems in the past, how did they deal with XYZ (find specific cases for XYZ)
- Give them the option to talk to the team
- Give the team the option to talk to the interviewee
- Make sure the person could really fit within the team, don't just value work
suggestion_content: Great job outlining your thoughts on the recruiting process! To deepen your reflection, consider exploring how your values align with team dynamics. What specific qualities do you think are essential for a candidate to truly fit into your team? This could help you articulate your vision even more clearly.
final_reflection:
During the finding process:
- Be as explicit as possible in the advertisement
- Showcase our own values and how we work in the hiring process/advert
- Distribute the advert in my own and others network
- Possibly find sb within the network

During interview process:
- Avoid standard procedures
- Talk about values, expectations, examples on how they work: e.g. how did they deal with problems in the past, how did they deal with XYZ (find specific cases for XYZ)
- Give them the option to talk to the team
- Give the team the option to talk to the interviewee
- Make sure the person could really fit within the team, don't just value work

topic_description: Please answer the following questions AFTER you have had your individual coaching session.
question: In about 300 words, please describe first the 2-3 key insights of your coaching session (eg. What did you realize that you were not aware of before? What beliefs were questioned? Where did you gain greater clarity?). Then describe the 2-3 key actions (eg. What will you do differently in the next semester? How will you show up differently? How will you organize yourself?). Also write down any other thoughts that you believe should be captured here because they are relevant to you.
reflection_snapshot:
So about my coaching, I would say the key insights would be more about wanting to do things to get my German better, because I can speak it and I know it but I focus too much about making mistakes and so I sometimes think about what I am about to say and then it's not the same topic that we are talking about so the reaction "isn't worth" anymore. So basically, I set myself goals to be more real when I react in German even if it's not perfect. Also the fact of embracing my mistakes will only lead me to interact even more with the others than I am currently and will help to show my entire personality which can be sometimes a little bit held in the back because of how I think too much about what I am going to say because when I'm speaking French (my native language) I tend to be a really expressive person who always have some kind of jokes and plays on words to make. And that is a consequent part of my personality. 
We also talked about the study abroad semester and how we have to be aware of the dates to choose in which semester we want to go abroad, so I will look into that when I choose. 
And I think it was interesting to have an external opinion about how I see things and about what I write down on the Rflects we have done in the semester. 
And it's always lovely to have someone saying to you that you see things in the right angle about your future ^^
So basically thank you for the coaching session
suggestion_content: It's great to see you engaging so thoughtfully with your coaching session! Your insights about embracing mistakes and being more expressive in German are valuable. What specific strategies can you implement to feel more comfortable making mistakes? Also, how might your expressive nature enhance your interactions in German?
final_reflection:
So about my coaching, I would say the key insights would be more about wanting to do things to get my German better, because I can speak it and I know it but I focus too much about making mistakes and so I sometimes think about what I am about to say and then it's not the same topic that we are talking about so the reaction "isn't worth" anymore. Also the fact of embracing my mistakes will only lead me to interact even more with the others than I am currently and will help to show my entire personality which can be sometimes a little bit held in the back because of how I think too much about what I am going to say because when I'm speaking French (my native language) I tend to be a really expressive person who always have some kind of jokes and plays on words to make. And that is a consequent part of my personality. 
We also talked about the study abroad semester and how we have to be aware of the dates to choose in which semester we want to go abroad, so I will look into that when I choose. 
And I think it was interesting to have an external opinion about how I see things and about what I write down on the Rflects we have done in the semester. 
And it's always lovely to have someone saying to you that you see things in the right angle about your future ^^

question: The things I struggle with are… and what support looks like is…
reflection_snapshot:
Not having visited Switzerland so far :) 

Nah, I'm kidding. That's not a struggle, but a wish I'll fulfill at some point. 
There are a few European countries I haven't yet visited.

But realistically speaking, it's not really a "struggle", but I'm continuously trying to improve my time management skills and to do something for myself every day. Having To Do lists does miracles, for me at least.

No support needed on that side, though!
suggestion_content: Great start with your reflection! It’s clear you have a sense of humor and are open about your experiences. question: Conditions I like to work in and the times / hours I like to work are…
suggestion_content: It's great to see you engaging with your working conditions and preferences! Your reflection could benefit from more depth. What specific aspects of your ideal work environment enhance your productivity? Also, how do your preferred hours align with your personal energy levels throughout the day?
final_reflection:
The starting date has been discussed already, but Nov 26 is a great. I’d generally much prefer to work from 15:00 to 18:00 CET if that overlaps with your working hours much enough, but we can also discuss about this during the onboarding meeting :)   

Nothing unusual about the conditions, though. You might already have a way to handle this kind of collaboration. I’d only expect us to have  
- a work communication channel (Teams, Slack, etc), even if we might also share phone numbers 
- a Jira board or something similar 
- written requirements for the work that is to be done (I might have questions or suggestions regarding various pieces of work, but everything should, in the end, be written so we’re sure we understand the same thing before starting the development)

question: How do you cultivate curiosity in your daily life? What practices or habits help you stay open to continuous learning and growth?
reflection_snapshot:
Curiosity has always been a cornerstone of my personal and professional growth. To cultivate this trait daily, I rely on intentional habits and practices that nurture my openness to new experiences and learning.

A foundational practice is staying engaged with diverse perspectives. My multilingual abilities, which include proficiency in languages like English, French, and Italian, encourage me to interact with people from different cultures. Whether coaching students as a language mentor or collaborating across international teams, these interactions continually expand my worldview. I see each conversation as an opportunity to learn something unexpected, whether it’s about a new cultural nuance or a fresh approach to problem-solving.

Another habit I prioritize is dedicating time to reflect on my experiences. As someone with extensive experience in communication and team management, I regularly analyze my actions and their outcomes, identifying areas for improvement. This reflective practice not only deepens my understanding of interpersonal dynamics but also pushes me to question assumptions and seek better approaches.

Engaging in structured learning also fuels my curiosity. Currently pursuing a Master’s degree in Business Psychology, I find that exploring topics like organizational development and employee potential aligns with my professional focus while also challenging me intellectually. I complement formal education with self-directed learning, such as reading about the latest HR trends or experimenting with tools like Trello for project management.

Finally, my interests outside of work, such as exploring European cultures or following football, keep me inspired. These passions remind me that curiosity isn’t confined to professional contexts—it’s about maintaining a mindset that embraces both small joys and big challenges.

Cultivating curiosity isn’t just about being open to new knowledge; it’s about actively seeking growth opportunities and embracing the unknown. This mindset ensures that I remain adaptable, resourceful, and continually evolving, both personally and professionally.
suggestion_content: You've done a fantastic job highlighting your curiosity and the practices that nurture it! To deepen your reflection, consider exploring how specific experiences have shaped your curiosity. What challenges have you faced in staying curious, and how have they influenced your growth? This could add valuable depth to your insights!
final_reflection:
Curiosity has been a driving force in my life, but staying curious hasn't always been easy - it's often been shaped and refined by specific experiences and challenges that have tested my commitment to learning and growth.

One of the most transformative periods for my curiosity was my time as a European Volunteer in Sweden. Living in Gävle, far away from familiar surroundings, I faced the challenge of adapting to a new culture and environment while making a meaningful contribution to a community-focused organisation. At first, the language barrier and cultural differences were intimidating. However, I leaned into my curiosity and used it as a tool to connect with others, learn the nuances of Swedish culture, and embrace the unexpected. This experience taught me that curiosity isn't just about seeking knowledge; it's about embracing discomfort as an opportunity to grow.

Similarly, working in fast-paced environments such as McKinsey & Company and Simon-Kucher required me to remain adaptable and open to continuous learning. Supporting senior partners meant dealing with high stakes and shifting priorities, which at times felt overwhelming. There were times when the pressure to get it done quickly made me stop being curious. However, these challenges pushed me to find creative solutions, explore better organisational strategies, and actively seek feedback. Each challenge reinforced my belief that curiosity thrives when coupled with resilience and a willingness to evolve.

An ongoing challenge has been balancing curiosity with focus. With so many areas of interest - languages, psychology, team development, and cultural exploration - it's tempting to spread myself too thin. I've learnt to channel my curiosity strategically, diving deep into areas that align with my professional goals, such as organisational psychology, while still indulging in personal interests to maintain balance.

These experiences have taught me that curiosity is not static; it's a skill that grows stronger through effort, reflection, and an openness to challenge. Ultimately, it's the setbacks and obstacles that deepen my commitment to staying curious and constantly evolving.

The provided student text already incorporates elements of the Gibbs reflective cycle, but there’s room for enhancement.

The question asked is: ```How do you cultivate curiosity in your daily life? What practices or habits help you stay open to continuous learning and growth?```

Student provided answer: ```Curiosity has always been a cornerstone of my personal and professional growth. To cultivate this trait daily, I rely on intentional habits and practices that nurture my openness to new experiences and learning.

A foundational practice is staying engaged with diverse perspectives. My multilingual abilities, which include proficiency in languages like English, French, and Italian, encourage me to interact with people from different cultures. Whether coaching students as a language mentor or collaborating across international teams, these interactions continually expand my worldview. I see each conversation as an opportunity to learn something unexpected, whether it’s about a new cultural nuance or a fresh approach to problem-solving.

Another habit I prioritize is dedicating time to reflect on my experiences. As someone with extensive experience in communication and team management, I regularly analyze my actions and their outcomes, identifying areas for improvement. This reflective practice not only deepens my understanding of interpersonal dynamics but also pushes me to question assumptions and seek better approaches.

Engaging in structured learning also fuels my curiosity. Currently pursuing a Master’s degree in Business Psychology, I find that exploring topics like organizational development and employee potential aligns with my professional focus while also challenging me intellectually. I complement formal education with self-directed learning, such as reading about the latest HR trends or experimenting with tools like Trello for project management.

Finally, my interests outside of work, such as exploring European cultures or following football, keep me inspired. These passions remind me that curiosity isn’t confined to professional contexts—it’s about maintaining a mindset that embraces both small joys and big challenges.

Cultivating curiosity isn’t just about being open to new knowledge; it’s about actively seeking growth opportunities and embracing the unknown. This mindset ensures that I remain adaptable, resourceful, and continually evolving, both personally and professionally.```

*Your task*
Let's work this out in a step-by-step way to be sure we have the right support. Provide reasoning first and then the coaching. You will conduct three steps internally, but make sure only show step four in your output.

*To complete the task, follow the three steps*
1. Identify the language in which the student has written their text. Provide your coaching in the same language as the student's text.
2. Identify the steps from the Gibbs reflective cycle that are already in the text and those that may be missing. Your feedback should address the elements that are missing. The feedback should encourage students to engage more with their reflection and improve their reflective writing skills.
3. Also help the student to progress on the subject-matter that the student is reflecting about. The coaching should include both the process of reflection and the content of the reflection.
4. Formulate your coaching based on the following instructions:
Start with something encouraging. If students only provide bullet points or short sentences encourage them to write more.

*Output instructions*
 - Start with something positive and encouraging.
 - Provide one to a maximum of two open questions (like Why, How and What) to engage more deeply with the reflections and the content of the reflection. Ensure your feedback is only up to 50 words (less is fine too).
 - Do not use bullet points.
 - Use an informal but polite language, be concise, and address the students in the second singular form.
 - If the student text is less than 20 words, state that it is too short to provide helpful feedback and provide one small idea to get started.


", "temperature": 0.4, "suggestion_type": "regular-suggestion", "time_to_generate": 2814}
question_clean: How do you cultivate curiosity in your daily life? What practices or habits help you stay open to continuous learning and growth?
reflection_snapshot_clean:
Curiosity has always been a cornerstone of my personal and professional growth. To cultivate this trait daily, I rely on intentional habits and practices that nurture my openness to new experiences and learning.

A foundational practice is staying engaged with diverse perspectives. My multilingual abilities, which include proficiency in languages like English, French, and Italian, encourage me to interact with people from different cultures. Whether coaching students as a language mentor or collaborating across international teams, these interactions continually expand my worldview. I see each conversation as an opportunity to learn something unexpected, whether it’s about a new cultural nuance or a fresh approach to problem-solving.

Another habit I prioritize is dedicating time to reflect on my experiences. As someone with extensive experience in communication and team management, I regularly analyze my actions and their outcomes, identifying areas for improvement. This reflective practice not only deepens my understanding of interpersonal dynamics but also pushes me to question assumptions and seek better approaches.

Engaging in structured learning also fuels my curiosity. Currently pursuing a Master’s degree in Business Psychology, I find that exploring topics like organizational development and employee potential aligns with my professional focus while also challenging me intellectually. I complement formal education with self-directed learning, such as reading about the latest HR trends or experimenting with tools like Trello for project management.

Finally, my interests outside of work, such as exploring European cultures or following football, keep me inspired. These passions remind me that curiosity isn’t confined to professional contexts—it’s about maintaining a mindset that embraces both small joys and big challenges.

Cultivating curiosity isn’t just about being open to new knowledge; it’s about actively seeking growth opportunities and embracing the unknown. This mindset ensures that I remain adaptable, resourceful, and continually evolving, both personally and professionally.
suggestion_content_clean: You've done a fantastic job highlighting your curiosity and the practices that nurture it! To deepen your reflection, consider exploring how specific experiences have shaped your curiosity. What challenges have you faced in staying curious, and how have they influenced your growth? This could add valuable depth to your insights!
final_reflection_clean:
Curiosity has been a driving force in my life, but staying curious hasn't always been easy - it's often been shaped and refined by specific experiences and challenges that have tested my commitment to learning and growth.

One of the most transformative periods for my curiosity was my time as a European Volunteer in Sweden. Living in Gävle, far away from familiar surroundings, I faced the challenge of adapting to a new culture and environment while making a meaningful contribution to a community-focused organisation. At first, the language barrier and cultural differences were intimidating. However, I leaned into my curiosity and used it as a tool to connect with others, learn the nuances of Swedish culture, and embrace the unexpected. This experience taught me that curiosity isn't just about seeking knowledge; it's about embracing discomfort as an opportunity to grow.

Similarly, working in fast-paced environments such as McKinsey & Company and Simon-Kucher required me to remain adaptable and open to continuous learning. Supporting senior partners meant dealing with high stakes and shifting priorities, which at times felt overwhelming. There were times when the pressure to get it done quickly made me stop being curious. However, these challenges pushed me to find creative solutions, explore better organisational strategies, and actively seek feedback. Each challenge reinforced my belief that curiosity thrives when coupled with resilience and a willingness to evolve.

An ongoing challenge has been balancing curiosity with focus. With so many areas of interest - languages, psychology, team development, and cultural exploration - it's tempting to spread myself too thin. I've learnt to channel my curiosity strategically, diving deep into areas that align with my professional goals, such as organisational psychology, while still indulging in personal interests to maintain balance.

These experiences have taught me that curiosity is not static; it's a skill that grows stronger through effort, reflection, and an openness to challenge. Ultimately, it's the setbacks and obstacles that deepen my commitment to staying curious and constantly evolving.

topic_description:
Herzlich Willkommen!
Wir freuen uns sehr, Dich bei unserem strukturierten Qualifizierungsprogramm TUM Science Manager (Level 2): Change Management & Transformation begrüßen und Dich auf Deiner learning journey begleiten zu dürfen.

Bei Fragen melde Dich bitte gern bei uns: careerdesign@lll.tum.de

Viele Grüße, Eva & Bernhard
question: Was sind deine 2-3 ganz persönlichen Lernziele? Und was können wir tun, um dich gut auf deinem Weg zu unterstützen und zu begleiten?
reflection_snapshot:
- Veränderungsprozesse im Team und darüber hinaus strukturierter gestalten und mir der Herausforderungen und Lösungswege besser bewusst sein, um proaktiv tätig werden zu können, insbesondere im Hinblick auf Digitalisierung.
- Grundlagen der Führung erlernen und neue Perspektiven entwickeln, um meinen Karriereweg zielgerichtet weiter zu gestalten.
suggestion_content: Es ist großartig, dass du dir klare Lernziele gesetzt hast! Um deine Reflexion zu vertiefen, könntest du darüber nachdenken, welche konkreten Schritte du unternehmen kannst, um deine Ziele zu erreichen. Was sind die größten Herausforderungen, die du dabei siehst? Und wie kannst du deine neuen Perspektiven konkret anwenden?
final_reflection:
- Veränderungsprozesse im Team und darüber hinaus strukturierter gestalten und mir der Herausforderungen und Lösungswege besser bewusst sein, um proaktiv tätig werden zu können, insbesondere im Hinblick auf Digitalisierung.
- Grundlagen der Führung erlernen und neue Perspektiven entwickeln, um meinen Karriereweg zielgerichtet weiter zu gestalten.

Wichtig wäre mir, ausreichend Zeit und Raum zu haben, um mit den anderen Teilnehmenden die Erkenntnisse reflektieren zu können und mein Netzwerk zu stärken.

topic_description:
Welcome to a new week, this time with the theme of “Appreciation”, the ability to relate to others and to the world with a basic sense of appreciation, gratitude and joy. This competence is part of the IDG Relating-Dimension.

We will reflect on the previous week, learn about the theme and plan the week ahead.

Why are there themed reflections?

Your innovative study program is aware of the importance of Inner Development in your Education and has decided to offer you Rflect to help you practice those Inner Competencies.

Inner Competences (some call it soft skills, personal development, etc.) are based on your thoughts, feelings, and behaviors. These competencies shape how we manage ourselves, relate to others, and respond to challenges. They are key to personal development, emotional well-being, and success in both personal and professional spheres. You can find out why there are important here.

Rflect helps you practice inner competencies outlined in the Inner Development Goals (IDG) and beyond.

Every week you will have one topic where you reflect on your personal learning journey and also on 1 of the 23 competencies outlined in the IDG Framework.

For the first semester(s) we will introduce those competencies broadly to you (with a few reflective questions). Later on, we will dive deeper into them and practice them with exercises and actions.
question:
Now look at your agenda for next week, what are the 3 things you want to learn for yourself? Think about the learning goals for this block and your assessment results.

Define 1 Action related to the theme of the week using the “take Action” button on the left bottom of this reflection that you will do each day this week to work towards these goals.

This week you could spend a few minutes each day writing down three things you’re grateful for, focusing on both small and significant aspects of your life.

You could also make it a habit to verbally thank or write a note of appreciation to at least one person each day, acknowledging their positive impact on your life or work.
reflection_snapshot:
Penser à remercier les gens à chaque fois qu'ils font quelque chose qui m'aide. Personnellement, je trouve que ça fait plaisir et que ça m'encourage à continuer d'agir.
Ecrire chaque jour une chose que je suis reconnaissante qui est arrivé durant la journée, cela me permettrait de voir chaque jour le côté positif dans ma vie. Je suis sûr que ça me boosterait !
suggestion_content: C'est super que tu te concentres sur la gratitude et l'appréciation des autres ! Pour approfondir ta réflexion, que dirais-tu de partager un exemple spécifique d'une situation où tu as ressenti de la gratitude récemment ? Cela pourrait enrichir ton écriture et te permettre de mieux comprendre l'impact de ces actions sur ta vie.
final_reflection:
Penser à remercier les gens à chaque fois qu'ils font quelque chose qui m'aide. Personnellement, je trouve que ça fait plaisir et que ça m'encourage à continuer d'agir.
Ecrire chaque jour une chose que je suis reconnaissante qui est arrivé durant la journée, cela me permettrait de voir chaque jour le côté positif dans ma vie. Je suis sûr que ça me boosterait !

question: How do you show appreciation to your peers? How would you like to feel appreciated? Have you told them this?
reflection_snapshot:
En leur montrant de l'intérêt, en les écoutant en m'intéressant à eux et à ce qu'ils font.
Lorsque les gens m'écoutent et montrent de l'intérêt pour ce que je fais et je dis.
Non, je ne leur ai pas spécifiquement parlé de mes besoins.
suggestion_content: C'est super que tu réfléchisses à l'importance de montrer de l'intérêt pour tes pairs ! Pour approfondir ta réflexion, pourquoi ne pas explorer comment tu pourrais exprimer tes besoins d'appréciation à tes amis ? Quelles actions spécifiques pourraient renforcer vos relations ? Cela pourrait enrichir ton écriture.
final_reflection:
En leur montrant de l'intérêt, en les écoutant en m'intéressant à eux et à ce qu'ils font.
Lorsque les gens m'écoutent et montrent de l'intérêt pour ce que je fais et je dis.
Non, je ne leur ai pas spécifiquement parlé de mes besoins.

Je pourrai peut-être les remercier quand ils montrent un réel intérêt pour ce que je dis ou fais.

topic_title: Block 2 Week #2: Start the week: Importance and urgency of tasks
topic_description:
Welcome to a new week in Rflect, this time with the focus on “Importance and urgency of tasks”.

As usual you start the week with questions on your motivation and needed support.

In this week we will work on determining the importance and urgency of tasks. By using the Eisenhower matrix you will learn to prioritize better and get more insight into how to organize your time effectively. You will discover which tasks are really important and which ones you can postpone or delegate. This skill will help you stay organized, reduce stress and better manage your study and workload. Let's get started!

question:
Think of a situation recently where you were discussing a topic (without your program or outside) in a heated way.

Do you feel the other person was open and applied critical thinking to really understand your position?

Do you think you were open and applied critical thinking to really understand their position?
What can you take from this reflection? How can you practice what you preach and motivate others to do the same?
reflection_snapshot:
Ich glaube, je emotionaler die Situation ist, desto weniger rational kann argumentiert werden. Beziehungsweise es ist schwieriger, sich auf Fakten und nicht auf die eigenen Gefühle zu konzentrieren. Das gilt für mich als auch für die meisten meiner Mitmenschen. 

Deshalb ist es wichtig, bei inhaltlich relevanten Diskussionen einen kühlen Kopf zu bewahren und nur auf der rationalen Ebene zu argumentieren. Das bedeutet auch, das alle Beteiligte ihre Beiträge objektiv und angemessen teilen sollen. Auf diese Weise wir die Diskussion konstruktiv und ist sinnvoll.
suggestion_content: Es ist großartig, dass du die Bedeutung von rationalen Argumenten in emotionalen Diskussionen erkannt hast! Um deine Reflexion zu vertiefen, frage dich: Was genau hat dich in dieser Diskussion emotional berührt? Und wie könntest du in Zukunft sicherstellen, dass alle Stimmen gehört werden?
final_reflection:
Ich glaube, je emotionaler eine Situation ist, desto schwieriger wird es, rational zu argumentieren. Es fällt dann schwerer, sich auf Fakten zu konzentrieren und nicht von den eigenen Gefühlen geleitet zu werden. Diese Herausforderung betrifft sowohl mich als auch die meisten meiner Mitmenschen.

Daher ist es bei inhaltlich relevanten Diskussionen entscheidend, einen kühlen Kopf zu bewahren und auf einer sachlichen Ebene zu argumentieren. Dies bedeutet auch, dass alle Beteiligten ihre Beiträge objektiv und angemessen einbringen sollten. Nur so kann eine Diskussion konstruktiv und zielführend sein.

question: (How) can you use mindfulness techniques to reduce stress and boost your presence in your everyday student life? Do you want to do this? Why yes/no? Do you already do this? Why yes/no?
reflection_snapshot: My everyday student life is full of family obligations, stressful work situations and of course my need to do sports. It often feels like a guided bus tour to me. Just from one stop to another - in one moment I jump out of the bus to take a photo of the Hallstätter Lake and just 30 minutes later I'm already in the city centre of Salzburg. It's beautiful, interesting, a wide range of different activities overwhelm me with impressions and still I'm just driven by those and I don't have the time to do it all in the way I think I need to do it. I want to go deeper with the study topics, I want to still read a book a month, I still want to be a caring father and for me I still want to be sporty. In preparation of the studies I started with some useful habits during the summer already and one of those is meditation. It helps me to stop the bus tour for 5 to 10 minutes a day. I meditate and reflect a difficult decisions, a learning or reflect how I could better be present or reflect better. It's nothing I would say I'm good at. It's also nothing I would say could help everybody, but it helps me at least strengthen my presence in all the hopp on hopp off situations of my daily bus tour.
suggestion_content: Your reflection is a great start! I appreciate how you’ve captured the whirlwind of your daily life and the steps you’re taking to incorporate mindfulness. How do you think your meditation practice could evolve to support your goals even more? What specific changes would you like to see in your daily routine?
final_reflection:
My everyday student life is full of family obligations, stressful work situations and of course my need to do sports. It often feels like a guided bus tour to me. Just from one stop to another - in one moment I jump out of the bus to take a photo of the Hallstätter Lake and just 30 minutes later I'm already in the city centre of Salzburg. It's beautiful, interesting, a wide range of different activities overwhelm me with impressions and still I'm just driven by those, and I don't have the time to do it all in the way I think I need to do it. I want to go deeper with the study topics, I want to still read a book a month, I still want to be a caring father and for me I still want to be sporty. In preparation of the studies, I started with some useful habits during the summer already and one of those is meditation. It helps me to stop the bus tour for 5 to 10 minutes a day. I meditate and reflect a difficult decision, a learning or reflect how I could better be present or reflect better. It's nothing I would say I'm good at. It's also nothing I would say could help everybody, but it helps me at least strengthen my presence in all the hop on hop off situations of my daily bus tour. 

"Go Deeper" is again a good help. How could my practice evolve and what changes in my routines would I like to see? 
Evolve is a good word and it's a difficult question, I don't have some specific goals towards meditation, I got to know guys who were really deep into these topics, I often found this some kind of strange or even to spiritual for me. I want to focus more during the time, but still be open to all the paths that open up. 
And changes to my routines - of course I'm not superman and I don't tick off all the boxes every day and I also think with the growing number of routines, it won’t be possible and sometimes there is a day off with something - what I like is that I'm very strict with myself, especially with ticking off - I still don't want to do things by halves.

question: Was nimmst Du für Dich aus der Exkursion mit?
reflection_snapshot:
Das Erlebnis in der virtuellen Welt ist beeindruckend real und wirkt sich auf den ganzen Körper aus. Sobald man über schmale Balken gehen muss, stellt sich ein Gefühl der Unsicherheit ein, obwohl es sich nur um eine Illusion handelt. Das Gehirn kann nicht zwischen virtueller und realer Welt unterscheiden, sodass auch das Fahren mit einem virtuellen Aufzug als intensives Erlebnis empfunden wird.

Erst am Ende wurde mir bewusst, wie wichtig die Zusammenarbeit in dieser Umgebung ist und wie viel effizienter man als Team agieren kann. Diese Erkenntnis ist eine wertvolle Lektion, die ich aus dieser Erfahrung mitnehme. Es wäre spannend, das Szenario noch einmal zu durchlaufen und dabei noch bewusster auf Teamarbeit zu setzen.

Dieses Setting fördert zweifellos den Teamgeist. Ich habe auch gelernt, dass man als Einzelkämpfer weniger erreicht. Während ich mich auf die Aufgabe konzentrierte, die Roboter zu bekämpfen, stellte ich überrascht fest, dass ich dabei auch meine Mitstudent:innen beschützte.

topic_description: Please conduct this session AFTER you have done the stress assessment.
question:
In the upcoming online session, we will take a closer look at the topic of stress. We will look at where it comes from and, above all, how we can deal with it in a healthy way.

After the online session, you will take part in your individual coaching session, in which you will have the opportunity to reflect on aspects that are relevant to you. This could be the topic of stress or another topic that you have reflected on in the recent weeks or something completely different. The coach will read your reflections in preparation. If you already have an idea of what you would like to talk about in the coaching session, please write it down here. The more specific you are, the better the coach can prepare.
reflection_snapshot: Mental health, anxiety,
suggestion_content: It's great that you're already thinking about mental health and anxiety! To deepen your reflection, consider exploring how these topics specifically affect you. What triggers your anxiety, and how do you currently cope with it? This could help you prepare for your coaching session.
final_reflection: The topics that come to mind are mental health, anxiety, and overcoming procrastination.
